fields.description: The Oruanui eruption of New Zealand's Taupō Volcano (also known as the Kawakawa eruption or Kawakawa/Oruanui event) was the world's most recent supereruption, and largest phreatomagmatic eruption characterised to date.

The Toba eruption (sometimes called the Toba supereruption or the Youngest Toba eruption) was a supervolcanic eruption that occurred about 74,000 years ago during the Late Pleistocene at the site of present-day Lake Toba in Sumatra, Indonesia. It was the last in a series of at least four caldera-forming eruptions at this location, with the earlier known caldera having formed around 1.2 million years ago.

Aso caldera (also known as Asosan, the Aso Volcano or Mount Aso, although the later term usually is used related to its currently active vents) is a geographical feature of Kumamoto Prefecture, Japan.

Bangladesh Liberation War (1970-1972). Western Asia. was an armed conflict sparked by the rise of the Bengali nationalist and self-determination movement in East Pakistan, which resulted in the independence of Bangladesh.The war began when the Pakistani military junta based in West Pakistan—under the orders of Yahya Khan—launched Operation Searchlight against East Pakistanis on the night of 25 March 1971, initiating the Bangladesh genocide.
World War II (1939-1945). Asia: Japan. The "Little Boy" bomb was dropped on Hiroshima on August 6, 1945.
World War II (1939-1945). Asia: Japan. The "Fat Man" bomb was dropped on Nagasaki on August 9, 1945.
World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Western Front: Invasion of Poland by Germany in 1939.
World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Western Front: Battle of France, May 10–June 25, 1940.
World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Western Front: Battle of Britain July 10 to October 31, 1940.
World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Western Front: Normandy landings (D-Day) in 1944, France.
World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Eastern Front: Invasion of the Soviet Union by Germany in 1941.
World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Eastern Front: The Battle of Stalingrad was a major World War II battle that took place from August 1942 to February 1943.

World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Eastern Front: The Battle of Kursk was a major World War II Eastern Front battle between the forces of Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union near Kursk in southwestern Russia during the summer of 1943.
World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Eastern Front: Liberation of Berlin in 1945.
World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Balkans: Invasion of Yugoslavia and Greece by Germany and Italy in 1941.

World War II (1939-1945). Europe, Balkans: Yugoslav resistance. In World War II, the Balkan Peninsula maintained its neutrality until 1941. That year, it was invaded and divided between Axis forces and two puppet regimes: Croatia and Serbia.
World War II (1939-1945). Africa, North Africa: Western Desert Campaign in June 1940. Tobruk and El Alamein, Egypt.

World War II (1939-1945). Africa, North Africa: The Second Battle of El Alamein (23 October – 11 November 1942) was a battle of the Second World War that took place near the Egyptian railway halt of El Alamein.
World War II (1939-1945). Africa, North Africa: Operation Torch (allied landing in Morocco and Algeria in 1942).

World War II (1939-1945). Asia and the Pacific, Pacific War: Attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941. The attack on Pearl Harbor was a surprise military offensive carried out by the Imperial Japanese Navy against the United States naval base at Pearl Harbor (Hawaii) on the morning of Sunday, December 7, 1941.

World War II (1939-1945). Asia and the Pacific, Pacific War: The Battle of Midway was an important air-naval battle of World War II that took place between June 4 and 7, 1942, when a large fleet of the Imperial Japanese Navy, commanded by Isoroku Yamamoto, attacked the American bases on the atoll of Midway in its campaign for the central Pacific Ocean.

World War II (1939-1945). Asia and the Pacific, Pacific War: The naval battle of Guadalcanal itself consisted of a sequence of combined sea and air attacks that lasted more than four days (from November 12 to 15, 1942), most of them in the area around the island of Guadalcanal. Guadalcanal very close to the island of Savo, in the Solomon Islands.

World War II (1939-1945). Asia and the Pacific, Southeast Asia: The Battle of Singapore, also known as the Fall of Singapore, took place in the Southeast Asian theater of World War II when the Empire of Japan invaded the British fortress of Singapore. The fighting lasted from February 8 to 15, 1942 and ended with the conquest of Singapore by Japanese troops.

World War II (1939-1945). Asia and the Pacific, Southeast Asia: The Malaya Campaign is the name given to the Japanese expansionist offensive that led to the occupation of Thailand and the expulsion of British troops from Malaya and Singapore. It began on December 8, 1941 and ended with the Battle of Singapore on January 31, 1942.

World War II (1939-1945). Asia and the Pacific, Southeast Asia: The Burma Campaign encompasses all the combats fought in British Burma, now Burma (or Myanmar), between the Allied forces and Japanese forces, supported by local independence movements at the beginning of 1942.

World War II (1939-1945). Asia and the Pacific, Southeast Asia: The Second Sino-Japanese War was a military conflict between the Republic of China and the Empire of Japan that was fought between July 7, 1937 and September 9, 1945, within the framework of World War II.

World War II (1939-1945). North Atlantic: The Battle of the Atlantic was the naval confrontation that had the Atlantic Ocean as the scene of operations, practically in its entirety, fought during the Second World War between the large German ships, the U-Boats commanded by Admiral Karl Dönitz and almost the entire of the British Royal Navy.

World War II (1939-1945). Mediterranean: The Battle of the Mediterranean was the name given to the naval campaign fought in the Mediterranean Sea during World War II, from June 10, 1940 to May 2, 1945.
